Gonopod (

Fig. 
4

A–C): Coxa with long distad lateral spine (
ls
) and a substantial metaplical flange (
mf
). Metaplical apex broad and round, with a process (
mp
) protruding mesally above arculus, and ending in a long anterior basad-posteriad-curving spine (
ms
) (see notes). Proplica ending apically in a distad lobe (
pl
) partly covered by metaplical spine. Telopodite: no spines or folds on basomere, telomere with very long basad proximal spine (
ts
) situated just after basomere. Telomere a fairly short elongate lamella, broader at basis, with a second much smaller lamella (
tl
) branching off from base of telomere. Solenomere slightly longer than telomere, first half appressed to the curving telomere, second half curving back towards base of telomere, so solenomere seems to rest loosely within telomere. Solenomere with longitudinal fluting, otherwise simple.
